04745nam a22005775i 9780774865326DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748653267 a10.59962/97807748653262doi  a(DE-B1597)661537  a(OCoLC)1155375280  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ1822.5.K43bB73 2020 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a305.4209942231 aBradbury, Bettina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCaroline's Dilemma :bA Colonial Inheritance Saga /cBettina Bradbury. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (362 p.) :b16 b&w photographs and 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tThe Bax and Kearney families – three generations -- tMap – location of Bax family and relatives, 1837–70 -- tIntroduction -- tMigration, Marriage and Station Life: Becoming Australian Colonisers -- tMigrations and Marriage -- tBroom Station, Mosquito Plains, South Australia, 1853–57 -- tLockhart Station, Western Wimmera, Victoria, 1858–65 -- tWidowhood: Contesting Edward’s will and his brothers’ influence -- tEdward’s death, his final wishes and religious warfare -- tLearning legal procedures -- tLeaving Lockhart Station -- tArrivals and new challenges -- tLater lives: Deaths and legacies -- tEndings -- tThe boys’ adult lives -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCaroline Kearney faced a heartbreaking dilemma. Caroline was a thirty-one-year-old mother of six when her husband died in Melbourne, Australia in 1865. Having no legal rights herself to the sheep station in Wimmera, Victoria that her late husband owned, she had great hopes that her sons would inherit it. But that was not to be. Her husband’s will, written on his deathbed, offered a reasonable annuity to support her and the children, but it came with a catch. To get that money, Caroline had to move to Ireland with her children and live in a house of her brothers-in-law’s choosing. English-born, Caroline had migrated to Australia with her family when she was only seventeen. She had never even been to Ireland. Her husband and his family – unlike her – were Catholic. This extraordinary book combines storytelling with a historian’s detective work. Pieced together from evidence in archives, newspapers, genealogical sites, legal records and old-fashioned legwork, Caroline’s Dilemma sheds new light on the workings of colonial gender relationships and family lives that spanned the nineteenth century globe. It reveals much about women’s property rights, migration, settler colonialism, the Irish diaspora, and sectarian conflict. It shows how one middle-class woman and her family fought to shape their own lives within the British Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInheritance and successionzAustraliaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWidowsxLegal status, laws, etc.zAustraliaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWidowszAustraliaxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aWomenzAustraliavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2020z978311127473708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311141765340uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486532640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774865326423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774865326/original  a978-3-11-127253-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-12747